2.1 Interface Overview
When you open Power BI Desktop you will see three views on the left sidebar:

Icon	View	What You Do Here
📊	Report View	Build visuals and design report pages
🗃️	Data View	Inspect your data as a table, add calculated columns
🔗	Model View	Build relationships between tables
Key panels in Report View:

Filters pane (left) — apply filters at visual, page, or report level
Visualizations pane (right) — pick chart types and assign fields
Fields pane (far right) — all your tables and columns live here
2.2 The Data Flow (How Power BI Works)
Data Source → Power Query → Data Model → Report
(Excel/SQL)   (Clean/Shape)  (Relationships) (Visuals)
Power Query runs first — it cleans and shapes your data before it loads
Data Model stores the cleaned data and manages relationships
Report reads from the model — it never touches the source directly
2.3 File Types
Extension	What It Is
.pbix	Standard Power BI file — contains data + report
.pbit	Template file — structure only, no data
.pbids	Data source connection file
💡 Always save .pbix files to SharePoint or OneDrive so your team can access them.

