3.1 What is Power Query?
Power Query is Power BI's data preparation engine. You use it to clean, reshape, and extend your data before it loads into the model. Every step you take is recorded and can be edited or deleted at any time.

💡 Rule: Never modify your source query directly. Always create a Reference query so your original data stays intact.

3.2 Common M Language Operations
Filter rows:

Table.SelectRows(Source, each [SCENARIO] = "BASE")
Remove columns:

Table.RemoveColumns(Source, {"PORTFOLIO", "UNUSED_COL"})
Keep specific columns:

Table.SelectColumns(Source, {"ID", "SCENARIO", "EL"})
Add a custom column:

Table.AddColumn(Source, "NewCol", each [EL] * 0.5, type number)
Append two tables:

Table.Combine({Table1, Table2})
Change column types:

Table.TransformColumnTypes(Source, {
    {"ID", type text},
    {"EL", type number}
})
Generate rows using a loop:

List.Generate(
    () => [qtr = 10, value = StartValue],
    each [qtr] <= 21,
    each [qtr = [qtr] + 1, value = [value] - Delta],
    each [PER_QTR = [qtr], TOTAL_ALLOWANCE = [value]]
)
3.3 Best Practices
✅ Create a Reference instead of duplicating queries
✅ Name every Applied Step clearly (right-click → Rename Step)
✅ Disable Load on staging/helper queries (right-click query → uncheck Enable Load)
✅ Use Advanced Editor for complex logic
❌ Never hard-code values that could change — use parameters instead
