4.1 What is a Star Schema?
A Star Schema organizes your data into two types of tables:

Fact Table — contains numbers you want to measure (e.g. sales, allowance, EL). Has many rows.
Dimension Table — contains descriptive attributes used to filter/slice (e.g. Date, Scenario, Segment). Has fewer rows.
        DimDate
           |
DimScenario — FactAllowance — DimSegment
           |
        DimPortfolio
💡 Think of the Fact table as the center of a star, with Dimension tables as the points.

4.2 Relationships
One-to-Many (most common) — one row in Dim matches many rows in Fact
Many-to-Many — avoid if possible, can cause unexpected filter behavior
Active vs Inactive — only one active relationship per table pair; use USERELATIONSHIP() in DAX to activate an inactive one
Cross-filter direction:

Single — filters flow one way (Dim → Fact). Default and recommended.
Both — filters flow both ways. Use carefully — can cause ambiguity.
4.3 Naming Conventions
Object	Convention	Example
Fact table	Prefix Fact	FactAllowance
Dimension table	Prefix Dim	DimScenario
Measure	Title Case	[Total Allowance]
Helper measure	Underscore prefix	[_Delta]
Columns	UPPER_SNAKE	TOTAL_ALLOWANCE
4.4 Calculated Columns vs Measures
Calculated Column	Measure
Calculated at	Data refresh	Query time (on demand)
Stored in	Model (uses RAM)	Not stored
Use for	Row-level categorization	Aggregations in visuals
Example	[Quarter Label] = "Q" & [PER_QTR]	[Total EL] = SUM([EL])
💡 Rule of thumb: If you can write it as a measure, do not use a calculated column.

