7.1 Choosing the Right Visual
Goal	Best Visual
Compare categories	Bar / Column chart
Show trend over time	Line chart
Show running totals / bridges	Waterfall chart
Show a single KPI number	Card
Show data in a table with subtotals	Matrix
Show part-to-whole	Donut / Pie (use sparingly)
Show rank changes over time	Ribbon chart
Show distribution	Histogram / Box Plot
7.2 Report Design Principles
One story per page — don't cram everything on one page
White space — leave breathing room between visuals
Max 3 colors — pick a palette and stick to it
Clear titles — every visual needs a descriptive title
Consistent font sizes — title 14pt, labels 10pt, axis 9pt
Left to right reading order — most important KPI top-left
7.3 Slicers & Interactivity
Slicer types: Dropdown (saves space), Tile (visual), Between (date ranges)
Sync slicers: View tab → Sync Slicers → apply across pages
Bookmarks: Used to simulate navigation buttons or toggle views
Drill-through: Right-click a data point → drill to a detail page
7.4 Waterfall Chart Pattern
Every waterfall bar needs three measures:

Measure	Purpose
Waterfall Start	Base of the bar (offset from zero)
Waterfall Amount	Visible size of the bar
Waterfall End	Top of the bar = Start + Amount
Navigation bars use Upper and Lower to control direction:

Waterfall Upper = MAX([Waterfall Start], [Waterfall End])
Waterfall Lower = MIN([Waterfall Start], [Waterfall End])
7.5 Dynamic Titles
Make your visual titles respond to slicer selections:

[Dynamic Title] =
"Total EL — Scenario: " & SELECTEDVALUE('Dim'[SCENARIO], "All Scenarios")
Assign this measure to the visual title field under Format → General → Title → fx.

